Section 1:
HCR 31 Text skip navigation SENATE PRESIDENT SENATORS COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS SENATE CLERK SENATE RULES HOUSE SPEAKER DELEGATES COMMITTEES VIDEO/AUDIO DISTRICT MAPS HOUSE CLERK HOUSE RULES HOUSE STAFF JOINT INTERIM COMMITTEES LEGISLATIVE ADMINISTRATOR LEGISLATIVE SERVICES DIVISION PUBLIC INFORMATION LEGISLATIVE AUTOMATED SYSTEMS DIVISION LEGISLATIVE AUDITOR'S OFFICE PERFORMANCE EVALUATION & RESEARCH DIVISION POST AUDIT DIVISION BUDGET DIVISION REGULATORY AND FISCAL AFFAIRS DIVISION CLAIMS COMMISSION CRIME VICTIMS RULE-MAKING REVIEW SPECIAL INVESTIGATIONS JUDICIAL COMP. COMMISSION JOINT RULES STAFF INFO BILL STATUS BILL STATUS BILL TRACKING STATE LAW WEST VIRGINIA CODE ACTS OF THE LEGISLATURE CODE OF 1931 WV CONSTITUTION US CONSTITUTION REPORTS AGENCY REPORTS AGENCY GRANT AWARDS PERFORMANCE EVALUATIONS POST AUDITS EDUCATIONAL CITIZEN’S GUIDE INTERNSHIP PROGRAM PAGE PROGRAM PUBLICATIONS PHOTO GALLERY CAPITOL HISTORY HOW A BILL BECOMES LAW CONTACT SENATE ROSTER HOUSE ROSTER PUBLIC INFO. NEWS RELEASES HELPFUL LINKS Introduced Version House Concurrent Resolution 31 History OTHER VERSIONS  - Committee Substitute | |  Email Key: Green = existing Code. Red = new code to be enacted HOUSE CONCURRENT RESOLUTION 31(By Delegate Hall and Lewis)[Introduced February 14, 2025; Referredto the committee on Energy and Public Works then Rules  ] Requesting the Division of Highways name bridge number 20-025/47-00.10 (20A-337), locally known as Dunbar Toll Bridge, carrying 10th Street over Kanawha River in Kanawha County, the "U. S. Army Lieutenant Colonel Quewanncoii "Que" C. Stephens, Sr. Memorial Bridge".Whereas, Lieutenant Colonel Quewanncoii Stephens, Sr. was born in Washington, D.C. in 1945 to EmmaRhaye Potts, a mathematics teacher; andWhereas, Lieutenant Colonel Quewanncoii “Que” C. Stephens, Sr., known as "Que," grew up in Plant City, Florida, where he attended Marshall High School, then was a third generation student at Florida A&M University where he was commissioned an Army Second Lieutenant before serving in Vietnam, later earning his Bachelor of Science in Social Science from Campbell College in North Carolina and his Master of Education in Counseling and Human Resources from Boston University; andWhereas, Stephens was commissioned an Armor Officer and departed for the Republic of Vietnam War. His first assignment was the 3rd Platoon, 2nd Armored Battalion, 11th Armored Calvary (Blackhorse) regiment. It was during this assignment that he was wounded in action during the TET Offensive and remained hospitalized for a period of three months due to his injuries and was awarded the Purple Heart. When he returned to the Republic of Vietnam to serve in the 44th Special Tactical Zone, 4th Corps, he served under Colonel David Hackworth, one of the most decorated Veterans in the military, author of "About Face" where he wrote about COL Que’s athletic prowess as a football quarterback in the "Rice Bowl" of 1971; andWhereas, COL Que served in numerous military assignments worldwide to include Fort Bragg, North Carolina where he attended and completed the Special Forces Officer Course, and Bamberg, Germany where he commanded Company B, 3rd Battalion 35th Armor. When he returned stateside, he was assigned to the Special Forces Officers Course (SFOC) as the Officer in Charge of Training (OIC), a position usually reserved for Infantry Officers, where he prepared officers to command Special Forces units. At this assignment, he completed the Command and General Staff College, Psychological Officers Course, and Jumpmaster School; andWhereas, Lieutenant Colonel Stephens, who served in the elite forces Green Berets, Special Forces, and Ranger, as well as Airborne as a Master Parachutist was the recipient of numerous military decorations, to include the Purple Heart, Bronze Star with 4 Oak Leaf Clusters, Meritorious Service Medal with one Oak Leaf Cluster, Army Commendation Medal with "V" device and 5 Oak Leaf Clusters, Ranger Tab, Jumpmaster Award, and Special Forces Tab to name a few; andWhereas, He then found his first love and that was to coach Pop Warner football. As the head coach, he led the Ft. Bragg Packers to the Pop Warner Support Bowl, another feat never accomplished. The game was seen around the world because it was televised prior to the Super Bowl in 1980; andWhereas, another true love for Lieutenant Colonel Stephens was mentoring future leaders. He served as Assistant Professor of Military Service and later Professor of Military Science at Prairie View A & M University. He was later reassigned to West Virginia State College, now West Virginia State University (WVSU), where he commissioned some of the nation’s finest officers. The program at WVSU had begun to decline, and LTC (Ret.) Stephens turned it around, producing two of the nation’s top cadets on two occasions; andWhereas, military retirement, "COL Que’s" leadership was recognized by two Governors (Caperton and Manchin) to serve in critical positions such as Executive Director of the Human Rights Commission (1980-1994) and West Virginia State’s Parole Board (1994 – 2008). He was selected as part of the Leadership West Virginia Class of 1993 and was a Governors Civil Rights Day Honoree in 2008. He was a champion of diversity and promoted human rights for all, receiving several special recognitions as a person concerned about the human rights of citizens throughout the State by numerous groups. He was constantly sought out to speak on matters concerning rights of people, race relations, and issues dealing with young people. An extremely hard worker, Stephens worked with the WV Division of Juvenile Services as the Quality Control Manager, After Care Supervisor, and Treatment and Program Manager for 18 southern counties. He worked until his death as a Community Resource Supervisor for the Bureau of Juvenile Services. In his position, Que oversaw aftercare services for youth reentering their community. He and his staff worked with youth and families from the time they were committed until a year post release. He ensured these youth had the educational, employment, mental health, medical and other needs met. His job was significant to him because it gave him purpose as he helped youth have a second chance after incarceration. He often spoke to schools encouraging students to do well and avoid the juvenile correction system, handing out his card and offering his help in advance. Although he just met the students, he would tell them he loved them and believed in them. He was a staunch youth advocate and truly believed in mentorship and support; and Whereas, Lieutenant Colonel Que was known for his love of photography, singing, working with youth, and serving on numerous boards that changed lives such as being appointed by the Governor to serve on the State of West Virginia Military Service Academy Board and entities that addressed issues that impacted the welfare of others to include serving as an ex-officio member of the Women’s Commission and serving in numerous suicide prevention roles. He loved serving as a Deacon at First Baptist Church in Charleston, WV, where he was also in charge the photo ministry and sang in the mass choir. One of his greatest loves was serving as a member of the Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Male Chorus where he sang bass. The group travelled extensively, sharing the joy of the Lord with their delighted audiences; andWhereas, Lieutenant Colonel Que passed away on January 21, 2024, surrounded by his family and friends. He was a loving father to Lieutenant Colonel Eurydice S. (Stephens) Stanley, PhD, his daughter; and his sons Quewanncoii C. Stephens II, and Quinton Cy Stephens. He was survived by his daughter Eurydice, grandchildren Grace and Christian Stanley, his partner of 16 years Nona Black, son and daughter in love Joe Black and Lilla Atkins, granddaughter Chloe Black, Uncle Clarence Richard "Dick" Potts (Mary) and a host of loving cousins, nieces, and nephews. His family was not limited by blood – it was extensive due to countless adopted "family" from his work, church, and numerous civic and Veteran organizations to include the American Legion, Prince Hall Freemasons, Rotary International, and Shriners; andWhereas, It is fitting that an enduring memorial be established to commemorate Lieutenant Colonel Quewanncoii "Que" C. Stephens, Sr. and his contributions to our state and country; therefore, be it Resolved by the Legislature of West Virginia:That the Division of Highways is hereby requested to name bridge number 20-025/47-00.10 (20A-337), locally known as Dunbar Toll Bridge, carrying 10th Street over Kanawha River in Kanawha County, the "U. S. Army Lieutenant Colonel Quewanncoii "Que" C. Stephens, Sr. Memorial Bridge"; and, be it Further Resolved, That the Division of Highways is hereby requested to have made and be placed signs identifying the bridge as the "U. S. Army Lieutenant Colonel Quewanncoii "Que" C. Stephens, Sr. Memorial Bridge"; and, be itFurther Resolved, That the Clerk of the House forward a copy of this resolution to the Commissioner of the Division of Highways. Bill Status  | Bill Tracking  | Legacy WV Code  | Bulletin Board  | District Maps  | Senate Roster  | House Roster  | Live  | Blog  | Jobs  | Links  | Home This Web site is maintained by the West Virginia Legislature's Office of Reference & Information.  | Terms of Use | Webmaster | © 2025 West Virginia Legislature ** Print On Demand Name: Email: Phone:


